"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079600","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-03-11","<p>Fixed sum charitable donations will be unaffected by the increased probate fees; the changes will only affect those estates where the deceased has left an entire estate, or a percentage of their residuary estate to charity. No estate will ever pay more than 0.5% of its value in probate fees.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-03-11T17:21:06.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079600/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079600/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079600/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-03-01","Probate: Charitable Donations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of increased probate fees on levels of charitable giving.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","227377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079601","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-07","<p>On 30 January, my Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care announced that the Pre-exposure Prophylaxis (PrEP) Impact trial would be expanded to 26,000 people. Rollout of additional places on the trial is now commencing and will be an important element in our HIV prevention efforts.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2019-03-07T16:32:32.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079601/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079601/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079601/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-01","HIV Infection: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 26 February to Question 222647 on HIV: Infection, what the timetable is for the review of the number of places available on the Pre-exposure Prophylaxis Impact trial by the PrEP Oversight Board.","false","Biography information for Lloyd Russell-Moyle","Brighton, Kemptown","Lloyd Russell-Moyle","227401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079604","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-03-11","<p>Fixed sum donations will not be affected by the proposed increase in fees. The changes will only affect those estates where the deceased has left an entire estate, or a percentage of their residuary estate to charity. The proposed fees are proportional to the value of the estate, meaning that no estate will ever pay more than 0.5% of its value in probate fees.</p><p> </p><p>However, we are aware of the figure cited by the Institute of Legacy Management and will carefully consider this assessment, should the Institute of Legacy Management be open to sharing their data with the department. We are unable to consider the merits of their conclusion otherwise, as the Probate Service does not collect data regarding charitable donations left in wills.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-03-11T17:32:32.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079604/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079604/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079604/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-03-01","Probate: Charities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will make an assessment of the merits of the conclusion of the Institute of Legacy Management in November 2018 that changes to probate fees could cost charities in the region of £10 million annually in legacy income.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","227417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079610","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-03-07","<p>The rate charged for and the difference between day and night units is a commercial decision for individual companies to make as long as suppliers set their rates within the limits of the price caps.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2019-03-07T13:12:18.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079610/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079610/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079610/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-01","Electricity: Prices","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the rate charged at night for a unit of electricity has increased compared to that charged for a day unit; and if so, why.","false","Biography information for Baroness Byford",,"Baroness Byford","HL14152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079611","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-03-15","<p>The Seasonal Workers Pilot is different to the previous Seasonal Agricultural Workers Scheme, which ran until 2013.</p><p> </p><p>The pilot will be run by two operators who will act as third party providers of labour. The Home Office have concluded that two scheme operators is the optimal number for managing this pilot. Defra ran a competitive selection process to select the two operators.</p><p> </p><p>The pilot is not designed to meet the full labour needs of the horticultural sector. Rather, the Government is seeking to evaluate the pilot’s ability to assist in alleviating labour shortages during peak production periods. We wish to assess fully this pilot before taking any decisions on future arrangements.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2019-03-15T12:10:32.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079611/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079611/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079611/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-03-01","Agriculture: Seasonal Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether consideration will be given to extending the pilot replacement Seasonal Agricultural Workers (SAWs) Scheme to allow previous licensed SAWs operators to recruit sufficient skilled seasonal manual workers for the coming growing season.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL14153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079612","Home Office","false","2019-03-14","<p>We have published an ambitious White Paper, setting out proposals for our future skills-based immigration system, including a new Temporary Worker route, open to all skill levels, to ensure UK businesses and employers have the staff they need, including seasonal workers.</p><p>Following a cooling off period, previous holders of a temporary short-term work visa will be eligible to apply for another temporary work visa to come to the UK.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2019-03-14T16:50:56.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079612/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079612/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079612/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-01","Agriculture: Seasonal Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the future EU workers visa scheme will allow farmers to employ seasonal workers on part-year contracts for consecutive years.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Whitchurch",,"Baroness Jones of Whitchurch","HL14154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079613","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-03-14","<p>The Government has not made any assessment of the advertisements placed by the University Hospital of Dusseldorf in Polish newspapers published in the United Kingdom.</p><p>However, we are clear that we want the 167,000 European Union nationals – including Polish nationals – who currently work in the health and social care sectors to stay in the UK after we leave the European Union. EU nationals are essential to the proper functioning of our health and social care services, and we care deeply about those who provide the vital care services that patients expect and deserve.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford",,"2019-03-14T11:21:10.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079613/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079613/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079613/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-01","Nurses: Migrant Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made, if any, of advertisements placed by the University Hospital of Dusseldorf in Polish newspapers published in the UK seeking to recruit Polish nurses currently working in the NHS by offering better pay, weather and food.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL14155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079614","Home Office","false","2019-03-14","<p>There are no plans to exempt international healthcare professionals from the requirement to pay the Immigration Health Surcharge. It is right that healthcare professionals subject to immigration control who come to the UK for more than six months make a fair contribution to the running of the NHS, as do other providers of essential public services, including teachers.</p><p>The Government recognises the major contribution that overseas health workers, and other highly skilled professionals make to the UK. Nurses currently benefit from an exemption from the minimum salary threshold for Tier 2 and a number of health professions appear on the Shortage Occupation List.</p><p>In addition, on 6 July 2018 we took action to exempt doctors and nurses entirely from the annual Tier 2 cap that applies to skilled workers. This change means that there is no limit on the number of overseas doctors and nurses needed in the UK who can be sponsored to work here. The Home Secretary has recently made clear that he has no plans to remove that exemption.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2019-03-14T16:59:09.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079614/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079614/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079614/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-01","Health Professions: Migrant Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford on 27 February (HL13739), what plans they have, if any, to abolish the health surcharge for overseas health workers in order to recruit more health professionals from overseas; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL14156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079615","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-11","<p>We remain deeply concerned about treatment of Jehovah's Witnesses in Russia. Of particular concern are two developments from February 2019: (1) the six year prison sentence handed down to Jehovah's Witness Dennis Christensen; and (2) reports of the torture of Jehovah's Witnesses while in detention. We worked with international partners to deliver EU statements to the Council of Europe and the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe on these issues. In these statements, we called on Russia to respect its international commitments on freedom of religion or belief, and to investigate the reports of torture, ensuring those responsible are held accountable. We continue to prioritise the promotion and protection of human rights, and will continue to make our concerns clear in bilateral interactions at all levels, where appropriate</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-03-11T15:32:43.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079615/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079615/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-01","Russia: Jehovah's Witnesses","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the treatment of Jehovah's Witnesses in Russia; and what representations they have made to the government of Russia about such treatment.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL14157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079616","Home Office","false","2019-03-15","<p>The information is not held centrally and to obtain it would exceed the disproportionate cost threshold.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2019-03-15T14:45:21.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079616/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079616/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-01","Proscribed Organisations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government on how many occasions members of organisations proscribed in UK legislation have been denied access to the UK to attend conferences organised by the Inter-Parliamentary Union.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell-Savours",,"Lord Campbell-Savours","HL14158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079617","Department for Transport","false","2019-03-12","<p>As stated in my written answer on 5 November 2018 (HL11004), it is long standing government policy not to comment in detail on security matters, including what criteria we use to assess security requirements at airports.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government continues to work closely with its Egyptian counterparts, sharing its expertise in establishing effective security arrangements at all Egyptian airports including Sharm el-Sheikh. We hope to be in a position to resume direct flights when the circumstances are right.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2019-03-12T14:42:33.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079617/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079617/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-01","Airports: Security","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Sugg on 5 November 2018 (HL11004), what criteria they use to assess the security requirements of airports.","false","Biography information for Lord Stone of Blackheath",,"Lord Stone of Blackheath","HL14159"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079618","Attorney General","false","2019-03-14","<p>The National Fund was set up by a trust deed in 1928. The Fund is held on trust for the purpose of reducing the National Debt.</p><p>The 1928 deed does not record who the founder was, and it is apparent from accompanying documents that they wished to remain anonymous.</p><p>Her Majesty’s Government therefore does not hold information about the identity of the donor who set up the Fund.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2019-03-14T17:12:40.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079618/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079618/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079618/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2019-03-01","National Fund","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they hold information about the identity of the donor who set up the National Fund.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL14160"
