"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079422","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-03-05","<p>On 29 November 2018 the Government introduced a ban of combustible materials in the external wall of buildings including blocks of flat, student accommodation and care homes more than 18 metres in height. The ban requires that all materials which become part of an external wall or specified attachment achieve European Class A2-s1, d0 or Class A1, other than those covered by exemptions. This means that materials are classified by smoke production as well as combustibility and production of droplets. These classifications impose the maximum possible restriction on smoke production.</p><p>In addition, the Government published, on 18 December, a call for evidence to form the basis for a technical review of Approved Document B (Fire Safety). Paragraphs 38 to 41 address the issue of smoke and toxicity. The call for evidence closed on 1 March 2019, the Department is in the process of reviewing the evidence provided.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","227107 ; 227108","2019-03-05T16:15:49.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079422/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079422/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079422/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-28","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 26 February 2019 to Question 224346 on Buildings: Insulation, whether he has made a recent assessment of (a) the combustibility of a range of common insulation materials and (b) the safety of those materials for use on buildings.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","227111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079423","Treasury","false","2019-03-05","<p>HMRC’s work on tackling international tax avoidance and on issues related to overseas crown dependencies and territories takes place across a range of areas within HMRC; ranging from compliance activity, litigation through to policy making. The majority of tax compliance work relating to these areas takes place in its Customer Compliance Group. There are currently around 25,000 people working in HMRC tackling all forms of non-compliance in the tax system.</p><p>This flexible resource gives HMRC the capability to effectively tackle compliance risks. HMRC officers are a flexible resource and may work on a number of cases involving several different customer groups’ behaviours and risks at any one time.</p><p>As such it is not possible to say how many staff work solely on these two specific areas.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2019-03-05T17:31:11.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079423/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079423/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079423/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-02-28","Taxation: British Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff at HMRC work on issues related to tax and the overseas crown dependencies and territories.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","227119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079424","Treasury","false","2019-03-05","<p>There are currently around 25,000 people working in HMRC tackling all forms of non-compliance in the tax system. They are a flexible resource and may work on a number of cases involving several different customer groups’ behaviours and tax risks at any one time to meet individual business needs.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC estimates that around 2,000-3,000 additional people work on matters related to VAT. This includes work on the policy, related processes, customer services, and other areas. As with HMRC’s compliance resource, people work flexibly and can be working on a range of taxes at any one point in time, not just VAT.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2019-03-05T17:31:01.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079424/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079424/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079424/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-02-28","VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff at HMRC work on matters related to Value Added Tax.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","227120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079425","Treasury","false","2019-03-05","<p>There are currently around 25,000 people working in HMRC tackling all forms of non-compliance in the tax system.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2019-03-05T17:20:38.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079425/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079425/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079425/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-02-28","Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff at HMRC work on issues related to tax compliance.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","227121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079426","Cabinet Office","false","2019-03-05","<p>The Cabinet Office is leading and coordinating the cross-departmental Prepare for EU Exit public information campaign to help fulfil the Government’s duty to inform citizens and businesses about how leaving the EU might affect them, and to advise them on the steps they may need to take to prepare. In the coming weeks and months, we plan to use a range of paid-for and no-cost channels to direct citizens and businesses to a dedicated area on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a> at Gov.uk/euexit.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Cabinet Office has undertaken to publish information relating to ongoing expenditure on the public information campaign as part of the department’s monthly data transparency releases. The latest release <em>(</em><em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cabinet-office-spend-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/cabinet-office-spend-data</a></em>) showed that as of 31 December 2018, expenditure relating to this campaign totalled £300,000. In conjunction, Cabinet Office has committed to disclose full costs regarding the TV advertising as part of these data releases in due course.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2019-03-05T11:32:01.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079426/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079426/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079426/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-02-28","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office,  what estimate the Government has made of the cost to the public purse of the planned television advertisements outlining how the UK's exit from the EU will affect the public.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","227162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079427","Home Office","false","2019-03-07","<p>The Home Office does not hold information centrally on how many migrant families were supported by local authorities under Section 17 of the Children Act 1989.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-03-07T18:23:41.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079427/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079427/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079427/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-02-28","Immigrants: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 25 February 2019 to Question 222020, how many migrant families were supported by local authorities under Section 17 of the Children Act 1989 in (a) 2015-16, (b) 2016-17, (c) 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","227112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079428","Home Office","false","2019-03-07","<p>These statistics are not included in Governments published migration statistics. The Government has no current plans to collect and collate the statistics in the manner requested as it would incur disproportionate cost to the public purse.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","227114 ; 227115","2019-03-07T18:48:21.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079428/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079428/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1079428/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-02-28","Immigrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 25 February 2019 to Question 222021, how many changes of circumstance applications to gain recourse to public funds were granted by his Department in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","227113"
